138 There are 8 different type of table access so there is no more than
139 combinations 2^8 = 256:

154
155 . STMT_WRITES_TEMP_NON_TRANS_TABLE
156
157 The unsafe conditions for each combination is represented within a byte
158 and stores the status of the option --binlog-direct-non-trans-updates,
159 whether the trx-cache is empty or not, and whether the isolation level
160 is lower than ISO_REPEATABLE_READ:
161
162 . option (OFF/ON)
163 . trx-cache (empty/not empty)
164 . isolation (>= ISO_REPEATABLE_READ / < ISO_REPEATABLE_READ)
165
166 bits 0 : . OFF, . empty, . >= ISO_REPEATABLE_READ
167 bits 1 : . OFF, . empty, . < ISO_REPEATABLE_READ
168 bits 2 : . OFF, . not empty, . >= ISO_REPEATABLE_READ
169 bits 3 : . OFF, . not empty, . < ISO_REPEATABLE_READ
170 bits 4 : . ON, . empty, . >= ISO_REPEATABLE_READ
171 bits 5 : . ON, . empty, . < ISO_REPEATABLE_READ
172 bits 6 : . ON, . not empty, . >= ISO_REPEATABLE_READ
173 bits 7 : . ON, . not empty, . < ISO_REPEATABLE_READ
174 */

507 /*
508 Class Query_expression represents a query expression.
509 Class Query_block represents a query block.
510 A query expression contains one or more query blocks (more than one means
511 that we have a UNION query).
512 These classes are connected as follows:
513 Both classes have a master, a slave, a next and a prev field.
514 For class Query_block, master and slave connect to objects of type
515 Query_expression, whereas for class Query_expression, they connect
516 to Query_block.
517 master is pointer to outer node.
518 slave is pointer to the first inner node
519
520 neighbors are two Query_block or Query_expression objects on
521 the same level.
522
523 The structures are linked with the following pointers:
524 - list of neighbors (next/prev) (prev of first element point to slave
525 pointer of outer structure)
526 - For Query_block, this is a list of query blocks.
527 - For Query_expression, this is a list of subqueries.
528
529 - pointer to outer node (master), which is
530 If this is Query_expression
531 - pointer to outer query_block.
532 If this is Query_block
533 - pointer to outer Query_expression.
534
535 - pointer to inner objects (slave), which is either:
536 If this is an Query_expression:
537 - first query block that belong to this query expression.
538 If this is an Query_block
539 - first query expression that belong to this query block (subqueries).
540
541 - list of all Query_block objects (link_next/link_prev)
542 This is to be used for things like derived tables creation, where we
543 go through this list and create the derived tables.
544
545 If query expression contain several query blocks (UNION now,
546 INTERSECT etc later) then it has a special query_block called
547 fake_query_block. It used for storing global parameters (like ORDER BY,
548 LIMIT) and executing union.
549 Subqueries used in global ORDER BY clause will be attached to this
550 fake_query_block, which will allow them to correctly resolve fields of
551 the containing UNION and outer selects.
552
553 For example for following query:
554
555 select *
556 from table1
557 where table1.field IN (select * from table1_1_1 union
558 select * from table1_1_2)
559 union
560 select *
561 from table2
562 where table2.field=(select (select f1 from table2_1_1_1_1
563 where table2_1_1_1_1.f2=table2_1_1.f3)
564 from table2_1_1
565 where table2_1_1.f1=table2.f2)
566 union
567 select * from table3;
568
569 we will have following structure:
570
571 select1: (select * from table1 ...)
572 select2: (select * from table2 ...)
573 select3: (select * from table3)
574 select1.1.1: (select * from table1_1_1)
575 ...
576

578 fake0
579 select1 select2 select3
580 |^^ |^
581 s||| ||master
582 l||| |+---------------------------------+
583 a||| +---------------------------------+|
584 v|||master slave ||

586 V| neighbor | V|

3420 /// Skip adding of the current token's digest since it is already added
3421 ///
3422 /// Usually we calculate a digest token by token at the top-level function
3423 /// of the lexer: MYSQLlex(). However, some complex ("hintable") tokens break
3424 /// that data flow: for example, the `SELECT /*+ HINT(t) */` is the single
3425 /// token from the main parser's point of view, and we add the "SELECT"
3426 /// keyword to the digest buffer right after the lex_one_token() call,
3427 /// but the "/*+ HINT(t) */" is a sequence of separate tokens from the hint
3428 /// parser's point of view, and we add those tokens to the digest buffer
3429 /// *inside* the lex_one_token() call. Thus, the usual data flow adds
3430 /// tokens from the "/*+ HINT(t) */" string first, and only than it appends
3431 /// the "SELECT" keyword token to that stream: "/*+ HINT(t) */ SELECT".
3432 /// This is not acceptable, since we use the digest buffer to restore
3433 /// query strings in their normalized forms, so the order of added tokens is
3434 /// important. Thus, we add tokens of "hintable" keywords to a digest buffer
3435 /// right in the hint parser and skip adding of them at the caller with the
3436 /// help of skip_digest flag.
3437 bool skip_digest;

3634 /**
3635 The LEX object currently serves three different purposes:
3636
3637 - It contains some universal properties of an SQL command, such as
3638 sql_command, presence of IGNORE in data change statement syntax, and list
3639 of tables (query_tables).
3640
3641 - It contains some execution state variables, like m_exec_started
3642 (set to true when execution is started), plugins (list of plugins used
3643 by statement), insert_update_values_map (a map of objects used by certain
3644 INSERT statements), etc.
3645
3646 - It contains a number of members that should be local to subclasses of
3647 Sql_cmd, like purge_value_list (for the PURGE command), kill_value_list
3648 (for the KILL command).
3649
3650 The LEX object is strictly a part of class Sql_cmd, for those SQL commands
3651 that are represented by an Sql_cmd class. For the remaining SQL commands,
3652 it is a standalone object linked to the current THD.
3653
3654 The lifecycle of a LEX object is as follows:
3655
3656 - The LEX object is constructed either on the execution mem_root
3657 (for regular statements), on a Prepared_statement mem_root (for
3658 prepared statements), on an SP mem_root (for stored procedure instructions),
3659 or created on the current mem_root for short-lived uses.
3660
3661 - Call lex_start() to initialize a LEX object before use.
3662 This initializes the execution state part of the object.
3663 It also calls LEX::reset() to ensure that all members are properly inited.
3664
3665 - Parse and resolve the statement, using the LEX as a work area.
3666
3667 - Execute an SQL command: call set_exec_started() when starting to execute
3668 (actually when starting to optimize).
3669 Typically call is_exec_started() to distinguish between preparation
3670 and optimization/execution stages of SQL command execution.
3671
3672 - Call clear_execution() when execution is finished. This will clear all
3673 execution state associated with the SQL command, it also includes calling
3674 LEX::reset_exec_started().
3675
3676 @todo - Create subclasses of Sql_cmd to contain data that are local
3677 to specific commands.
3678
3679 @todo - Create a Statement context object that will hold the execution state
3680 part of struct LEX.
3681
3682 @todo - Ensure that a LEX struct is never reused, thus making e.g
3683 LEX::reset() redundant.
3684 */
